comments.body:
The script did 
export SLURM_CPUS_PER_TASK=$((256/$PPN))
and export SLURM_CPUS_PER_TASK=$((128/$PPN)) seems to be running

More info from customer:
I checked on some of the other node types we’re testing and all of the AMD Turin system (which have total core counts of 256 and up) report the bulk service disabled message.  We have two other Intel system types we are testing with CN5000, the SR650 V3 (node n1814) and SR650 V4 (node n2003).  n1814 has 128 total cores  (with HT off) and n2003 has 128 total cores  (with HT off).  Neither of these have the bulk service disabled message, and they have good performance between them (though n2003 is using a copper splitter cable, so its running a 2x link, but it got ~ 382 Gbps bi-directionally at an 8MB message size, which is a good result for a 2x link).

One other difference between the systems with bad and good performance—for the bad performance, those are Intel 6980P GNR-AP CPUs.  The ones with good performance have Intel 6972P GNR-AP CPUs.  Each has two sockets.  The total core count in the bad case is 512 and for the good case is 384 (HT is on in both cases).  It seems like this might be relevant, since where this message comes from is the “chip.c” source file in the
 
static int set_up_context_variables(struct hfi1_devdata *dd)
 
function, and there is some interaction with the number of CPU cores it seems here:
 
                int count = get_num_user_contexts(dd, pidx);
                /*





                 */
                if (!hardware_pidx_available(dd, pidx))
                        count = 0;
                if (count < 0)
                        count = cpumask_weight(&node_affinity.real_cpu_mask);
                n_usr_ctxts[pidx] = count;
